data.content:
磁盘
A magnetic storage device that requires initialization and formatting before it can store data.<SEP>Disk is a storage device that supports high-speed data transfer and random access, classified as a block device and shared device in operating systems.

磁盘主引导记录
A special sector at the beginning of a disk that contains a partition table, boot code, and a flag indicating which partition to boot from.

簇
A group of adjacent sectors combined to improve efficiency in data storage and access (called a block in Linux).

扇区
A small unit of storage on a disk, typically composed of a header, data area, and trailer, used for read/write operations.

逻辑格式化
A process that sets up a file system on a partition, including initializing free and allocated space, root directory, and managing free block information (also known as high-level formatting).

低级格式化
A process that divides a disk into sectors, enabling the disk controller to perform read/write operations (also known as physical formatting).

分区
The process of dividing a disk into one or more logical sections called partitions, each defined by a starting sector and size.

柱面
A set of corresponding tracks on multiple disk platters, used in disk partitioning.

自举程序
A small program that initializes hardware and loads the operating system kernel into memory during system startup.

备用块
A reserved sector used to replace a bad sector, maintaining data integrity through logical replacement.

系统磁盘
A synonym for a bootable disk that contains the operating system and can initiate system startup.

主引导记录
A sector at the beginning of a disk (sector 0) containing boot code, partition table, and boot flag (used in Windows systems).

坏块
A damaged sector on a disk that cannot be used for data storage.

启动磁盘
A disk with a bootable partition that can be used to start the operating system.

引导扇区
The first sector of a bootable partition, loaded after the MBR, to continue the boot process.

引导块
A fixed-position area on a disk that stores the full boot program, enabling system startup after initial ROM code execution.

FAT表
A data structure used to track allocated and free clusters on a disk, particularly in FAT-based file systems.

ROM
A non-volatile memory chip that stores the initial bootstrap code used during system startup.<SEP>ROM (Read-Only Memory) is a type of non-volatile memory used to store fixed code, such as basic device driver functions.

Windows系统
A computer operating system that stores boot code in the first sector of a disk, known as the Master Boot Record (MBR).

Device Allocation
Device allocation is the process of assigning physical devices to user I/O requests, aiming to maximize device utilization while preventing deadlock.

Physical Device
Physical Device is a tangible hardware component connected to the system that can be allocated for I/O operations.

Device Control Table
Device Control Table (DCT) is a data structure that stores attributes of each physical device, including device type, identifier, status, pointer to controller table, retry count or time, and queue head pointer.

Channel Control Table
Channel Control Table (CHCT) is a data structure that records the status and configuration of each I/O channel, allowing the operating system to manage channels efficiently.

Controller
Controller is a hardware component that manages one or more physical devices and interfaces between the processor and devices.

Logical Unit Table
The Logical Unit Table (LUT) is a system component that maps logical device names to physical device names and device driver entry addresses.<SEP>Logical Unit Table (LUT) maps logical device names to physical device names and contains the entry address of the device driver.

Controller Control Table
Controller Control Table (COCT) is a data structure that stores information for managing each device controller, enabling the operating system to control and monitor controllers.

System Device Table
The system device table is a centralized record that tracks all physical devices available in the system, used in conjunction with user-specific LUTs.<SEP>System Device Table (SDT) is a global data structure that records all physical devices connected to the system, with one entry per physical device.

Channel
Channel is a communication path between the processor and device controller, enabling data transfer.

Virtual Device
Virtual Device is a software-implemented device that behaves like a shared device, allowing multiple processes to use it simultaneously.

FCFS Algorithm
FCFS Algorithm is a device allocation strategy that assigns devices to processes based on the order of their I/O requests, first-come, first-served.

I/O Request
I/O Request is a user-level or system-level request for input/output operations on a device, triggering device allocation.

Process Control Block
Process Control Block (PCB) is a data structure that stores the state and information of a process, including its I/O wait status.

Highest Priority First Algorithm
Highest Priority First Algorithm is a device allocation method that prioritizes processes with higher priority, using FCFS among equal-priority requests.

Exclusive Device
Exclusive Device is a type of device that can be allocated to only one process at a time and remains with that process until released.

Shared Device
Shared Device is a type of device that can be concurrently accessed by multiple processes, requiring proper scheduling.

Safe Allocation Method
Safe Allocation Method ensures deadlock prevention by blocking a process until its I/O operation completes, resulting in serial CPU and I/O execution.

Unsafe Allocation Method
Unsafe Allocation Method allows processes to continue running after sending I/O requests, potentially leading to deadlock but enabling concurrent device usage.

Logical Device Name
The logical device name is a user-defined identifier for a device that is used to reference the device in the system.<SEP>Logical Device Name is an abstract identifier used by processes to request I/O operations, independent of physical device identity.

Channel Queue
Channel Queue is a waiting list for processes awaiting channel availability during device allocation.

Controller Queue
Controller Queue is a waiting list for processes waiting for a controller to become available.

System Device Table Entry
System Device Table Entry is a record in the System Device Table that describes a single physical device's configuration and status.

Device Queue
Device Queue is a waiting list for processes that are awaiting device allocation, managed based on allocation strategy.<SEP>Device queue is a waiting list for I/O requests when a device is busy, managed by the device driver.

Physical Device Name
The physical device name refers to the actual hardware device name recognized by the system.<SEP>Physical Device Name is the real, unique identifier of a physical hardware device recognized by the operating system.<SEP>Physical device name is the actual identifier of a hardware device used to access its driver.

Device Driver
Device Driver is a software component that enables communication between the operating system and a physical device.<SEP>Device driver is a communication program between the I/O system and device controller, responsible for translating abstract I/O requests into specific commands and managing device operations.

Device Driver Entry Address
The device driver entry address is the memory location where the device driver code begins, enabling system access to the physical device.

Single System LUT
The single system LUT is a configuration where only one LUT exists for the entire system, sharing device assignments across all processes.

User-Specific LUT
The user-specific LUT is a configuration where each user has an individual LUT, allowing independent device naming and assignment.

Multi User System
A multi user system is an environment where multiple users operate simultaneously, allowing duplicate logical device names when using separate LUTs per user.

Single User System
A single user system is an environment where only one user operates at a time, requiring unique logical device names to avoid conflicts.

操作系统
操作系统是管理计算机硬件与软件资源的系统软件，影响设备独立性软件与设备驱动程序的实现方式。

设备公有操作
设备公有操作是指所有设备共有的基本操作，如读、写、控制等，由设备独立性软件统一处理。

I/O系统
I/O系统是计算机系统中负责管理输入与输出操作的核心架构。

运行效率
运行效率是评估操作系统、设备独立性软件和设备驱动程序性能的重要指标。

设备驱动程序
设备驱动程序是I/O系统中位于设备独立性软件下层的软件组件，负责与特定硬件设备交互。<SEP>Device driver is a hardware-specific program that executes system commands to drive I/O devices and serves as the communication bridge between I/O processes and device controllers.

设备独立性软件
设备独立性软件，也称与设备无关的软件，是I/O系统的最高层软件，负责执行所有设备的公有操作。<SEP>Device independence software offers a uniform interface between user programs and device drivers, manages device naming, protection, allocation, and release, and supports device management and data transfer.

功能实现差异
功能实现差异指某些本应由设备独立性软件实现的功能可能被分配给设备驱动程序实现，取决于系统设计权衡。

Interrupt Driven Method
The interrupt driven method allows I/O devices to signal the CPU when data is ready, enabling the CPU to perform other tasks while waiting.

Program Direct Control Method
The program direct control method involves CPU-controlled I/O operations through polling, where the CPU continuously checks the device status until data is ready.

Data Register
The data register in the device controller temporarily stores data read from or written to an I/O device.<SEP>The Data Register (DR) temporarily stores data during the transfer between I/O devices and memory in the DMA process.

Interrupt Signal
An interrupt signal is a notification sent from a device controller to the CPU indicating that data is ready.<SEP>An interrupt signal is a hardware signal sent by a device (e.g., DMA controller or I/O channel) to request CPU attention, typically after completing a task.

CPU
The CPU is the central processing unit responsible for executing instructions and managing I/O operations.<SEP>CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the primary processor in a computer system responsible for executing instructions and managing operations.<SEP>CPU is the central processing unit responsible for executing instructions and processing data.<SEP>CPU refers to the central processing unit, known for its high-speed operations in computing systems.

Device Controller
The device controller manages data transfer between an I/O device and the CPU or memory.<SEP>Device controller is a hardware component responsible for managing and executing commands sent by the device driver.

I/O Control
I/O control refers to the management of data transfer between devices and the host computer.

I/O Device
An I/O device is a hardware component that sends or receives data to/from the host system.<SEP>An I/O device is a peripheral component that sends or receives data to or from a computer system, involved in data transfer operations.<SEP>I/O Device refers to any hardware component that transfers data between the computer and external systems, such as disk drives or network interfaces.

Memory
Memory is the storage component in a computer system where data is stored for processing.<SEP>Memory refers to the main storage in a computer system where data and instructions are held temporarily during processing.<SEP>Memory refers to the physical RAM used to house temporary data, including disk cache and buffers.

Context
Context refers to the state of a running process, including registers and program counter, saved during interrupt handling.

Data Transfer
Data transfer is the process of moving data between devices, controllers, and memory.

Word (Byte)
A word or byte is the basic unit of data transferred during I/O operations, typically handled by the CPU and device controller.

Serial Operation
Serial operation refers to the sequential execution of tasks, such as CPU waiting for I/O completion, which limits parallel processing.

Instruction Cycle
The instruction cycle is the sequence of steps a CPU follows to execute an instruction.

DMA Controller
A DMA controller is a hardware component that manages data transfer between I/O devices and memory independently of the CPU.

DMA Way
DMA (Direct Memory Access) is a method that allows I/O devices to transfer data directly to and from memory without CPU intervention, improving efficiency and enabling parallel operations.

Memory Address Register
The Memory Address Register (MAR) in the DMA controller holds the memory address to which data will be read from or written to.

Command/Status Register
The Command/Status Register (CR) is a register in the DMA controller used to store commands and the current status of data transfer operations.

Data Counter
The Data Counter (DC) in a DMA controller tracks the number of data units remaining to be transferred.

Data Block
A data block is the basic unit of data transfer in DMA and channel operations, representing a group of contiguous data words or bytes.

Channel Program
A channel program is a sequence of channel instructions stored in memory that defines the I/O operations to be executed by the I/O channel.

Channel Instruction
A channel instruction is a specific command executed by the I/O channel to perform a defined I/O task.

Parallel Operation
Parallel operation refers to the ability of multiple components (CPU, I/O devices, DMA, channel) to perform tasks concurrently to improve system efficiency.

Direct Memory Access
Direct Memory Access is a data transfer method that enables high-speed I/O operations by allowing devices to access memory directly without CPU involvement.

I/O Channel
An I/O channel is a special-purpose processor that executes channel programs to manage I/O operations independently of the CPU.

Device Status
Device status is information about the current operational condition of a device, monitored and reported by the device driver.

Write Command
Write command is an abstract I/O request used to send data to a device.

I/O System
I/O system is the layer that manages input and output operations in a computer system, interfacing with device drivers and applications.

Read Command
Read command is an abstract I/O request used to retrieve data from a device.

Interrupt Request
Interrupt request is a signal sent by a device controller to notify the system of an event such as task completion or error.<SEP>An interrupt request is a signal sent by a hardware device (like the keyboard) to the CPU to request immediate attention.

Abstract I/O Request
Abstract I/O request refers to high-level commands like read or write issued by upper-layer software, which need translation into device-specific operations.

Interrupt Handling
Interrupt handling is the process by which the device driver responds to interrupt signals from the device controller and initiates appropriate actions.<SEP>Interrupt handling is the process by which the operating system responds to hardware interrupts, such as those from the keyboard, to manage I/O events.

Device Driver Entry Point
Device driver entry point is the starting address or function used to access a specific device driver in the system.

Unified Interface
Unified interface is a standardized communication method between device drivers and the operating system.

PCB
PCB (Process Control Block) is a data structure that stores information about a process, including its state, scheduling details, and pending I/O requests.

Disk
Disk is a physical disk with a magnetic coating used for data storage, where data is stored in concentric tracks and sectors.<SEP>Disk is a block device used for storing data in blocks, supporting high-speed and random access.

Magnetic Track
Magnetic Track is a concentric circle on a disk surface where data is stored, each as wide as the magnetic head.

Disk Drive
Disk Drive is a device containing the magnetic head arm, spindle for rotation, and electronic components for data input/output.

Sector
Sector is a fixed-size unit of storage on a magnetic track, typically 1KB in size, and is the smallest addressable unit on a disk.<SEP>A sector is a subdivision of a track on a disk, storing a fixed amount of data and used as the smallest unit for read/write operations.

Fixed Head Disk
Fixed Head Disk is a type of disk where each track has a dedicated magnetic head.

Cylinder
Cylinder is a set of tracks with the same radius across multiple disk surfaces in a stacked disk assembly.

Magnetic Head
Magnetic Head is a conductive coil responsible for reading and writing data on a disk during operation.

Disk Platter
Disk Platter is a single physical disk with a magnetic surface used in disk storage systems.

Moving Head Disk
Moving Head Disk is a disk with a single magnetic head that moves radially to access different tracks.

Fixed Disk
Fixed Disk is a disk where the platters are permanently enclosed within the disk drive.

Winchester Disk
Winchester Disk is an early type of disk invented by IBM, featuring movable heads and fixed platters.

Data Access Process
Data Access Process involves moving the head arm to the target cylinder, activating the appropriate head, and reading/writing data as the disk rotates under the head.

Data Storage Density
Data Storage Density refers to the amount of data that can be stored per unit area on a disk, which increases from the outer to the inner tracks due to fixed angular division of sectors.

Disk Addressing
Disk Addressing uses a three-part identifier (Cylinder Number · Surface Number · Sector Number) to locate specific data blocks on a disk.

Removable Disk
Removable Disk is a disk system where the platters can be removed and replaced.

IBM
IBM is the organization credited with developing the first Winchester disk.

Inter-Track Gap
Inter-Track Gap is the physical spacing between adjacent magnetic tracks to prevent read/write interference and ensure data accuracy.

Inter-Sector Gap
Inter-Sector Gap is the space between adjacent sectors on a track, used to avoid overlap and ensure correct data sector recognition.

Surface
Disk addressing includes the surface number to identify the specific disk face where data resides.

I/O Interface
I/O interface is the interface between the I/O system and higher-level components, facilitating communication and data transfer.

Interrupt Driven I/O
Interrupt driven I/O is a common method used by character devices, where the CPU is interrupted upon I/O completion.

Memory Mapped Interface
Memory mapped interface allows access to disk via memory byte arrays instead of traditional read/write operations.

Block Device Interface
Block device interface manages devices that transfer data in blocks, such as disk drives, and supports operations like open, read, write, and close.

DMA I/O
DMA I/O is a method used by block devices, allowing direct data transfer between memory and device without CPU intervention.

Character Device Interface
Character device interface is used for devices that transfer data in character units, such as keyboards and printers, and supports operations like get, put, and in-control instructions.

Blocking I/O
Blocking I/O is a mode where the calling process is suspended until I/O operation completes, then it is resumed.

Network Device Interface
Network device interface provides network connectivity and communication capabilities, often implemented through socket interfaces.

Non Blocking I/O
Non blocking I/O is a mode where the process is not suspended during I/O and periodically checks the status of the operation.

Keyboard
Keyboard is a character device used for input, transmitting data one character at a time.

Character Device
Character device is a type of hardware device that transfers data in individual characters, such as keyboards and printers.

Block Device
Block device is a type of storage device that transfers data in fixed-size blocks, such as hard drives and SSDs.

Network Device
Network device is a hardware component enabling network connectivity, such as network interface cards.

Printer
Printer is a character device used for output, processing data in character units.<SEP>Printer is a non-shared device managed through SPOOLing to allow multiple users to submit print jobs simultaneously.

Socket Interface
Socket interface is a standardized network communication mechanism used by operating systems.

Character Buffer
Character buffer is a memory area used to store data temporarily when dealing with character devices due to their sequential access nature.

In-Control Instruction
In-control instruction is a generic command provided in the character device interface to handle the diverse operations of various character devices.

Open and Close Operations
Open and close operations are provided in the character device interface to manage exclusive access and mutual sharing of devices.

Disk Scheduling Algorithm
Disk scheduling algorithm is a technique used to manage the order of disk I/O requests to minimize seek time and improve performance.

Shortest Seek Time First
Shortest Seek Time First (SSTF) is a disk scheduling algorithm that selects the request closest to the current head position to minimize seek time.

Circular Scan Algorithm
Circular Scan (C-SCAN) algorithm moves the disk head in a single direction, servicing requests until it reaches the end, then quickly returns to the beginning without servicing requests.

Scan Algorithm
Scan algorithm, also known as the elevator algorithm, moves the disk head in one direction until it reaches the end of the disk, then reverses direction and serves requests.

First Come First Served
First Come First Served (FCFS) is a simple disk scheduling algorithm that processes requests in the order they arrive.

Rotational Latency
Rotational latency is the time it takes for the desired sector to rotate under the read/write head after the head reaches the correct track.

Transfer Time
Transfer time is the time needed to read or write data from or to the disk once the head is positioned.

Seek Time
Seek time is the time required for the disk read/write head to move to the specified track.

Look Algorithm
Look algorithm is an improved version of the Scan algorithm that stops moving when it reaches the last request in the current direction, rather than reaching the disk end.

Disk Cache
Disk cache is a memory buffer used to temporarily store frequently accessed data to speed up disk I/O operations.<SEP>Disk Cache is a technology used by operating systems to improve disk I/O performance by storing frequently accessed data in memory, reducing direct disk access.

Pre-reading
Pre-reading involves loading the next block into memory while the current block is being processed to reduce future access delays.

Sector Interleaving
Sector interleaving is a technique to alternate physical sector numbering so that multiple consecutive logical blocks are physically spaced apart to reduce rotational latency.

Physical Block Arrangement
Physical block arrangement optimizes the placement of file blocks on the disk to minimize seek time, especially for contiguous files.

Disk Surface Skew
Disk surface skew is a method where sectors on adjacent disk surfaces are offset to allow immediate read access when switching between surfaces.

C-Look Algorithm
C-Look algorithm is a variation of C-SCAN that stops at the last request in a single direction before returning to the starting point.

Delayed Writing
Delayed writing stores data in a buffer with a delay flag, releasing the buffer until it is actually written to disk.

Virtual Disk
Virtual disk, also known as a RAM disk, uses memory space to emulate a disk drive for faster access.

RAID
RAID (Redundant Array of Independent Disks) is a data storage technology that combines multiple physical disks into a single logical unit for improved performance and reliability.

Disk Head
The disk head is the mechanical component that reads from or writes to the disk surface, responsible for moving to the correct track and aligning with the correct sector.

Disk Read/Write Operation
A disk read/write operation refers to the process of reading data from or writing data to a disk, encompassing seek time, rotational latency, and transfer time components.

Disk Rotation Speed
Disk rotation speed is the rate at which the disk platters spin, affecting rotational latency and data transfer time.

Average Seek Time
Average seek time is the mean time required for the disk head to move to the desired track across all possible tracks.

Platter
A platter is a disk-shaped component in a hard drive that stores data magnetically, with one or more surfaces used for data storage.

Track
A track is a concentric circle on a disk surface where data is stored, and the disk head moves to access data on a specific track.

I/O Operation
I/O operation refers to input/output activities between a program and external devices, involving data transfer between user space and kernel space.

Count
Count specifies the maximum number of bytes to be read during a system call.

Trap Instruction
A trap instruction is a mechanism that switches the CPU from user mode to kernel mode to execute system calls.

read
read is a system call that performs low-level I/O operations, taking file descriptor, user buffer, and count as parameters.

Kernel Buffer
The kernel buffer is a buffer located in kernel space used to temporarily store data during I/O operations.

User Buffer
The user buffer is a buffer located in user space, associated with functions like scanf, for storing input data before processing.

File Descriptor
File descriptor (fd) is an identifier used by the operating system to access open files or I/O devices.

scanf
scanf is a C library function used to read formatted input from standard input, associated with a user buffer.

Kernel Mode
Kernel mode is a privileged execution state of the CPU where system calls and device drivers operate.

User Mode
User mode is a restricted execution state where user programs run, requiring system calls to access kernel resources.

Process P
Process P is the executing process that initiates an I/O operation and gets blocked during the I/O wait phase.

Keyboard Interrupt Handler
The keyboard interrupt handler is a kernel-level routine that processes incoming keyboard input and transfers data to the kernel buffer.

Ready Queue
The ready queue is a data structure that holds processes waiting to be scheduled for execution.

Device Driver Layer
The device driver layer is the kernel component responsible for directly controlling hardware devices during I/O operations.

Keyboard I/O Interface
The Keyboard I/O Interface is hardware that receives input from the keyboard and forwards data to the CPU via interrupt.

C Language Function Library
The C language function library is a collection of standard functions, including scanf, that provide high-level interfaces for system operations.

System Call Service Routine
The system call service routine is a kernel-level function that handles system calls, manages transitions between user and kernel modes, and coordinates I/O operations.

Blocked State
Process P enters the blocked state when it waits for I/O completion.

Single Buffer
Single Buffer is a buffering technique where one buffer is allocated per I/O request to manage data input and output.

Level 2 Cache
Level 2 Cache is a larger, slightly slower cache than Level 1, located outside the CPU core but still on the processor chip.

Level 1 Cache
Level 1 Cache is a small, high-speed memory located within the CPU core to store frequently accessed data.

Block
Block refers to a fixed-size unit of data used in disk storage and memory operations.<SEP>A block is a unit of data organization in flash memory, composed of multiple pages, where data is erased at the block level.

Buffer
Buffer is a temporary storage area used to hold data during transfer between devices or processes, helping to manage speed mismatches.<SEP>A buffer is a block of memory used to temporarily hold data during transfer between devices or processes.

Double Buffer
Double Buffer is a buffering technique that uses two buffers to allow overlapping of I/O operations with data processing.

Data Granularity
Data Granularity refers to the size of data units processed in a system, which may differ between devices and memory.

Circular Buffer
Circular Buffer is a data structure consisting of multiple buffers linked in a loop, used to manage continuous data flow with in and out pointers.

Device Management Subsystem
Device Management Subsystem is a component of the operating system responsible for handling I/O device operations.

Output
Output refers to the operation of sending data from the system to a device.

Input
Input refers to the operation of receiving data from a device into the system.

Interrupt
Interrupt is a signal sent to the CPU to indicate that an I/O operation has completed or requires attention.

System Memory
System Memory is the primary working memory of the computer, used by processes and system components including buffers and caches.

Circular Queue
A circular queue is a data structure where multiple buffers are linked in a loop, with each buffer pointing to the next, and the last pointing back to the first.

Output Queue
The output queue holds buffers containing data to be transmitted to an output device.

Out Pointer
The out pointer tracks the first full buffer from which data can be read.

Input Queue
The input queue holds buffers that have been filled with incoming data and are ready for processing.

In Pointer
The in pointer tracks the first available empty buffer where new data can be written.

Buffer Pool
A buffer pool is a management mechanism that oversees multiple buffers, containing a control data structure and operational functions, and allows shared access across multiple processes.

Hin Work Buffer
The hin work buffer is used to receive and store incoming data during input operations.

Empty Buffer Queue
The empty buffer queue is a list of unused buffers ready to be filled with data.

Sin Work Buffer
The sin work buffer is used to extract data from input buffers for processing.

Hout Work Buffer
The hout work buffer is used to store output data until it is sent.

Data Extraction Process
The data extraction process involves retrieving a buffer from the input queue, reading its data, and returning it to the empty queue after use.

Sout Work Buffer
The sout work buffer is used to retrieve output data from a filled buffer for transmission.

Cache
A cache is a high-speed storage that holds copies of data for faster access, located between high-speed and low-speed devices.

Data Output Process
The data output process involves taking an empty buffer, filling it with output data, and placing it onto the output queue.

Data Input Process
The data input process involves taking an empty buffer from the empty queue, filling it with data, and moving it to the input queue.

High-Speed Device
A high-speed device is a component with fast access time, such as a processor or memory.

Output Retrieval Process
The output retrieval process involves taking a filled buffer from the output queue, extracting its data, and returning it to the empty queue.

Low-Speed Device
A low-speed device is a peripheral or storage device with slower access times, such as a disk or network interface.

逻辑设备名
Logical device name is a abstract identifier used in device-independent software, allowing flexible device assignment and I/O redirection.

用户层软件
User layer software provides an interface for user interaction, enabling users to invoke I/O-related library functions to operate devices through system calls.

用户层
User layer is the highest level of the I/O software hierarchy, where user applications interact with the system through library functions.

I/O软件层次结构
I/O software hierarchy is a structured approach to designing input/output software with clarity, portability, and adaptability, consisting of four distinct layers.

设备独立性
Device independence, also referred to as device independence, enables applications to use logical device names without being tied to specific physical devices.

中断处理程序
Interrupt handler is a program triggered when an I/O operation completes, responsible for context switching, testing interrupt sources, reading device status, and updating process state.

物理设备名
Physical device name refers to the specific identifier of a physical hardware device, which is mapped from a logical device name during device operations.

系统调用
System calls are interfaces that allow user-level software to request services from the operating system.

缓冲管理
Buffer management is the process of managing memory buffers to facilitate efficient data transfer between devices and memory.

进程上下文切换
Process context switching involves saving and restoring the state of a process when handling interrupts or system calls.

设备释放
Device release is the process of freeing a device after use, ensuring availability for other processes.

设备状态
Device state is the current operational status of a device, including readiness, error, or busy conditions, which is monitored by the interrupt handler.

差错控制
Error control is the mechanism responsible for detecting and handling errors during device I/O operations.

设备分配
Device allocation refers to the process of assigning a device to a requesting process, managed through device independence software.

设备命名
Device naming is the process of assigning names to devices to support identification and access in device-independent operations.

设备保护
Device protection ensures that access to devices is controlled and secure based on user permissions and system policies.

中断信号
Interrupt signal is a notification sent by a device controller to the CPU to indicate the completion of an I/O operation.

I/O进程
I/O process refers to the logical entity responsible for managing input and output operations in the system.

设备控制器
Device controller is the hardware component responsible for managing the operation of a specific device and communicating with the CPU.<SEP>Device controller is a hardware component responsible for managing interaction between the CPU and I/O devices, consisting of interfaces and logic for command processing.

字符设备
Character devices transfer data one character at a time, typically featuring low transfer rates, non-random access, and commonly using interrupt-based I/O methods, such as keyboards and printers.

高速设备
High-speed devices transfer data at rates from hundreds of kilobytes to gigabytes per second, including storage devices like disks and optical drives.

中速设备
Medium-speed devices transfer data at rates from thousands to tens of thousands of bytes per second, such as laser printers.

操作系统设计
Operating system design involves the development and structuring of system software to efficiently manage hardware resources, particularly focusing on complexity in I/O device management.

块设备
Block devices are storage devices that transfer data in fixed-size blocks, such as hard drives and magnetic tapes, characterized by high transfer rates and random access capabilities.

I/O设备
I/O devices are external devices that either input data into a computer or output data from a computer, encompassing a wide variety of hardware with different functionalities.

人机交互设备
Human-computer interaction devices enable communication between users and computers, such as keyboards, displays, and printers.

低速设备
Low-speed devices have data transfer rates ranging from a few bytes to hundreds of bytes per second, including input devices like keyboards and mice.

存储设备
Storage devices are used for preserving data, including magnetic disks, tapes, and optical discs.

网络通信设备
Network communication devices facilitate data exchange between computers, such as network interface cards and modems.

I/O接口
I/O interface, also known as a device controller, acts as a bridge between the CPU and external devices, managing data exchange and device control.

共享设备
Shared devices allow multiple processes to access them simultaneously, generally utilizing time-sharing mechanisms, such as disk drives.

独占设备
Dedicated devices can only be used by one process at a time, typically low-speed devices like printers, until they are released.

虚拟设备
Virtual devices are created by transforming dedicated devices into shared ones through SPOOLing technology, allowing multiple logical devices to be derived from one physical device.

数据线
Data lines are signal lines used to transfer data between the CPU and the device controller.

地址线
Address lines are signal lines used to specify the memory or I/O device address during communication between CPU and device controller.

控制线
Control lines are used to carry command and status signals between the CPU and the device controller.

数据寄存器
Data registers are used to temporarily store input data from devices or output data to be sent to devices.

I/O逻辑
I/O logic is a component within the device controller responsible for decoding I/O commands received from the CPU and managing device operations.

状态寄存器
Status registers hold device execution results or current state information, accessible by the CPU for monitoring.

控制寄存器
Control registers are writable by the CPU to initiate commands or modify device operation modes.

独立编址
Independent addressing is a method where I/O ports have their own address space separate from main memory, using dedicated I/O instructions.

统一编址
Unified addressing, also called memory-mapped I/O, integrates I/O port addresses into the main memory address space, allowing I/O devices to be accessed using standard memory instructions.

并行接口
Parallel interface is a type of I/O interface that transmits multiple bits simultaneously over multiple lines.

程序查询接口
Programmed I/O interface is a control method where the CPU continuously polls the device to check its status before data transfer.

串行接口
Serial interface is a type of I/O interface that transmits data bit by bit over a single line.

不可编程接口
Non-programmable interface is an interface with fixed functionality that cannot be modified by software.

DMA接口
DMA interface is a control method that allows direct memory access, enabling data transfer between memory and devices without CPU intervention.

中断接口
Interrupt interface is a control method where the device signals the CPU via interrupts when it is ready for data transfer.

可编程接口
Programmable interface is an interface that can be configured or reprogrammed by software to adapt to different devices or operations.

磁带
Magnetic tape is a sequential storage device used for data backup and archival, classified as a block device with high capacity but slow access time.

光盘
Optical disc is a storage medium that uses laser technology to read and write data, typically classified as a block device.

调制解调器
Modem is a network communication device that converts digital signals into analog signals for transmission over telephone lines and vice versa.

网卡
Network interface card (NIC) is a hardware component that connects a computer to a network, enabling communication over wired or wireless connections.

Unified Addressing
Unified addressing, also known as memory-mapped I/O, integrates I/O ports into the main memory address space, allowing shared access via standard memory instructions.

Main Memory Address Space
The main memory address space is a portion of the total address space allocated for memory storage, partially used for I/O port addresses in unified addressing.

I/O Port Decoding
I/O port decoding refers to the process of interpreting I/O port addresses for device communication, which is simpler in isolated addressing schemes.

Address Space
Address space represents the range of addresses available for memory and I/O devices in a computer system, with two types: independent and unified.

Independent Addressing
Independent addressing separates I/O ports and memory into distinct address spaces, requiring dedicated I/O instructions and control signals.

Speed of Addressing
Speed of addressing refers to the efficiency with which addresses are accessed, faster in independent addressing due to simpler decoding.

Dedicated I/O Instructions
Dedicated I/O instructions are specialized CPU instructions used to access I/O ports, which are present only in independent addressing.

Flexibility in Programming
Flexibility in programming is enhanced in unified addressing since I/O operations use the same instructions as memory operations.

Control Signal Complexity
Control signal complexity refers to the number of distinct control signals required by the CPU, higher in independent addressing due to separate I/O and memory signals.

Two Independent Address Spaces
Two independent address spaces refer to the separation of memory and I/O address ranges, a fundamental characteristic of independent addressing.

Decoding Circuit Complexity
Decoding circuit complexity refers to the intricacy of circuits used to map addresses to devices, higher in unified addressing due to overlapping address mapping.

Address Space Occupancy
Address space occupancy indicates how much of the main memory space is used for I/O port addresses, reducing available memory in unified addressing.

Memory-Mapped I/O
Memory-mapped I/O is another term for unified addressing, where I/O ports are treated as part of the main memory address space.

打印机
Printers are typical examples of dedicated devices that can only be used by one process at a time.

SPOOLing技术
Virtual devices are created using SPOOLing technology, transforming dedicated devices into shared ones.

修改进程状态
Interrupt handler updates the process state to reflect I/O completion and enables resumption of the interrupted process.

统一接口
Device independence software provides a unified interface to the user layer or file layer, enabling device-independent operations.

Flash Translation Layer
The flash translation layer translates logical block read/write requests from the CPU into physical read/write control signals for the underlying flash memory device, functioning as a disk controller.

Solid State Disk
Solid State Disk (SSD) is a storage device based on flash memory technology, consisting of one or more flash memory chips and a flash translation layer.

Flash Memory Chip
A flash memory chip is a component of SSDs that stores data and replaces the mechanical drive in traditional hard disks.

Static Wear Leveling
Static wear leveling is a technique that reassigns data in idle blocks for read operations, allowing newer blocks to handle writing tasks and improving wear distribution.

Dynamic Wear Leveling
Dynamic wear leveling is a type of wear leveling that prioritizes writing data to flash blocks with fewer erase cycles, thereby balancing wear across blocks.

Wear Leveling
Wear leveling is a technique used in SSDs to distribute write and erase operations evenly across all flash memory blocks to prevent premature wear and extend device lifespan.

Page
A page is the smallest unit of data that can be read from or written to a flash memory device, with data written on a page-by-page basis.

Random Write
Random write refers to the process of writing data to non-sequential locations in storage, which is slow in SSDs due to the need to erase entire blocks before rewriting.

Erase Cycle
An erase cycle is the process of clearing data from a flash memory block, which is a slow operation and contributes to wear in SSDs.

Flash Memory Lifetime
Flash memory lifetime refers to the finite number of write/erase cycles a flash memory block can endure before failing.

Semiconductor Storage
Semiconductor storage refers to memory technology based on integrated circuits, such as flash memory used in SSDs.

Mechanical Drive
A mechanical drive is a traditional hard disk with moving parts used for data storage, replaced by SSDs in modern systems.

Peripheral Control Machine
A specialized machine used in SPOOLing systems to manage data transfers between devices and storage.

SPOOLing Technology
SPOOLing technology is an operating system technique that resolves the speed mismatch between CPU and I/O devices by converting exclusive-use devices into shared ones using disk storage and buffer management.

Input井
Input井is a storage area on disk simulating offline input, used to receive data from input devices.

Input Buffer
Input Buffer is a memory area that temporarily holds data from input devices before being transferred to the input井.

Output Buffer
Output Buffer is a memory area that temporarily holds data from output井before sending it to the output device.

Output井
Output井is a storage area on disk simulating offline output, used to hold output data from programs.

I/O Devices
I/O devices are input/output peripherals with lower operational speeds compared to the CPU.

Input Process
Input Process simulates a peripheral control machine by transferring data from input devices to the input buffer and then to the input井.

SPOOLing Management Process
SPOOLing Management Process handles print job requests by allocating disk space and managing job queues.

井管理程序
井管理程序controls the exchange of information between jobs and disk井, coordinating SPOOLing operations.

Output Process
Output Process simulates a peripheral control machine by transferring data from memory to output井and then to the output device via output buffer.

SPOOLing File Queue
SPOOLing File Queue is a list of print job entries awaiting processing, managed by the SPOOLing system.

User Request Print Table
User Request Print Table is a data structure that stores print job details and is linked to the SPOOLing file queue.

Disk Buffer Area
Disk Buffer Area is a reserved portion of disk space used to temporarily hold data during SPOOLing operations.

Virtual Device Function
Virtual Device Function is a capability enabled by SPOOLing, allowing exclusive devices to be used concurrently by multiple users.

Space for Time
Space for Time is a design principle where storage space is used to improve processing speed and efficiency.
